{{Infobox UK legislation |short_title=The Children and Young Persons Act 1908 |parliament=Parliament of the United Kingdom |long_title=An Act |statute_book_chapter=1908 c. 67 |introduced_by= |territorial_extent=United Kingdom |royal_assent= |commencement= |repeal_date= |amendments= |related_legislation= |repealing_legislation= |status=Current |original_text=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Edw7/8/67/contents/enacted |legislation_history= |}}
The '''1908 Children's Act''', also known as '''Children and Young Persons Act''', part of the [[Prevention of Cruelty to, and Protection of, Children Act 1889|Children's Charter]] was a piece of government legislation passed by the [[United Kingdom general election, 1906|Liberal government]], as part of the [[British Liberal Party]]'s [[liberal reforms]] package. The Act was informally known as the '''Children's Charter''' and surrounded controversy.
It established [[juvenile court]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.intriguing-history.com/childrens-act/|title=1908 Children’s Act was created to protect the poorest children in society from abuse|publisher=Intriguing History|language=English|date=12 January 2012|accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref> and introduced the registration of [[foster parents]], thus regulating [[baby-farming]] and [[wetnurse|wet-nursing]] and trying to stamp out [[infanticide]]. Local authorities were also granted powers to keep poor children out of the [[poorhouse]]/[[workhouse]] and protect them from abuse. The act also prevented children working in dangerous trades and prevented them from purchasing cigarettes and entering [[pubs]]. The act also prevented children from learning criminal "tricks of the trade" in adult prisons, where children were often sent to serve time if a crime had been committed. Instead the Children's Charter had allocated [[Borstals]]. It eventually led to many councils setting up [[social services]] and [[Orphanages]].
