[[File:Seal of the United States Department of Justice.svg|thumb|right|200px|Seal of the Department of Justice]] The '''Computer Crime and Intellectual Property Section''' (CCIPS) is a section of the [[United States Department of Justice Criminal Division|Criminal Division]] of the [[United States Department of Justice|U.S. Department of Justice]] in charge of investigating [[computer crime]] ([[Hacker (computer security)|hacking]], [[Computer virus|viruses]], [[Computer worm|worms]]) and [[intellectual property]] crime and specializing in the search and seizure of [[digital evidence]] in computers and on networks.
The Section has had recent{{when|date=July 2018}} success. A conviction was handed down by a [[New Jersey]] jury in the case of [[Christopher Rad]], who organized an international securities fraud ring, and stock manipulated through [[botnets]].<ref name=FBI>{{cite web|title=Organizer of International Securities Fraud Ring Perpetrated Through Botnets and Stock Manipulation Convicted|url=https://www.fbi.gov/newark/press-releases/2012/organizer-of-international-securities-fraud-ring-perpetrated-through-botnets-and-stock-manipulation-convicted|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|accessdate=19 December 2015}}{{Usgovpd}}</ref><ref>https://milkyway.cs.rpi.edu/milkyway/team_display.php?teamid=111994</ref>
