The '''Conspiracy and Protection of Property Act 1875''' (38 & 39 Vict. c.86) is an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] relating to [[labour relations]], which together with the [[Employers and Workmen Act 1875]], fully [[decriminalised]] the work of [[trade union]]s. Based on an extension of the conclusions of the [[Cockburn Commission]], it was introduced by a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government under [[Benjamin Disraeli]].<ref name="governments">[http://www.bsos.umd.edu/gvpt/lpbr/subpages/reviews/curthoys105.htm Review of Governments, Labour, and the law in mid-Victorian Britain: the trade union legislation of the 1870s] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516084033/http://www.bsos.umd.edu/gvpt/lpbr/subpages/reviews/curthoys105.htm |date=2006-05-16 }}, Mark Curthoys</ref>
The Act held that a trade union could not be prosecuted for act which would be legal if conducted by an individual.<ref>[http://www.spartacus.schoolnet.co.uk/Lconspiracy.htm Conspiracy & Protection of Property Act], Spartacus Education</ref> This meant that labour disputes were civil matters, not for consideration by [[criminal court]]s.<ref name="governments" /> One result of this was that [[Picketing (protest)|picketing]] was decriminalised.<ref>[http://www.unionhistory.info/timeline/1850_1880.php Timeline:1850-1880], TUC history online, Professor Mary Davis, Centre for Trade Union Studies, London Metropolitan University</ref> The law also made certain forms of [[stalking]] illegal.<ref>[http://www.callnetuk.com/home/dashmee/Act.htm Excerpt from the Conspiracy, and Protection of Property Act, 1875] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060401075219/http://www.callnetuk.com/home/dashmee/Act.htm |date=2006-04-01 }}, Unfair Discrimination in the Scottish State Education System</ref>
Sections 6 and 7 of this Act were repealed for the [[Republic of Ireland]] by the [[Non-Fatal Offences Against the Person Act]], section 31 and Schedule.
The Act has been repealed by the [[Statute Law (Repeals) Act 2008]] (c.12), Schedule 1, Part 3.
