{{for|the Canadian chain|United Cigar Stores Limited}} [[Image:United-Cigar-Wake-Up-America.jpeg|thumb|On April 19, 1917, the [[cowcatcher]] of the [[Flatiron Building]] United Cigar Store was transformed into a mock fort for the "Wake up America Day" parade.]]
{{Lead too short|date=November 2018}}
'''United Cigar Stores''' was a [[Chain store|chain]] of [[cigar]] stores in the United States that in its first quarter-century grew to nearly 3,000 shops. It eventually became part of the corporation that bought [[Marvel Comics]] and its parent company [[Magazine Management]] from their founder in 1968.
==History== Brothers Charles A. Whelan and George J. Whelan founded a tobacco [[Wholesaling|wholesale]] firm in [[Syracuse, New York]], in 1901, eventually turning to retail. By 1926, the chain had nearly 3,000 stores.<ref name=Time1926>{{cite news |title=Salesmen |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=December 20, 1926|url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,711536,00.html|archivedate=May 22, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180522211155/http://content.time.com/time/subscriber/article/0,33009,711536,00.html|deadurl=no}}</ref> Though initially specializing in cigars, it eventually sold many other items, such as [[Mickey Mouse]] watches and [[shoe tree]]s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Business: Schulte & Specialties |work=Time|date= November 29, 1937|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,758501,00.html|archivedate= October 25, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025205605/http://content.time.com/time/subscriber/article/0,33009,758501,00.html|deadurl=no}}</ref> The chain represented the interests of the Consolidated Tobacco Company, the tobacco trust that controlled the [[American Tobacco Company]] and others. In September 1903 a settlement was reached with the chain's competitors and all competition ended.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Consolidated Tobacco Company and affiliated corporations. 'The Tobacco Trust.'|pages=69–96ff |title=The Truth About The Trusts: A Description and Analysis of the American Trust Movement |authorlink=John Moody (financial analyst)|first=John |last=Moody|publisher= Moody Publishing |location= New York |date=1904 |oclc=1832950 }}</ref>
In August 1929, the chain and the affiliated Whelan Drug chain, founded by two of Charles' Whelan's sons, was sold to brothers George Kenan and Frederick Kenan Morrow.<ref>{{cite news|title=Milestones, Dec. 22, 1941|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=December 22, 1941|4=|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,931998,00.html|archivedate=May 22, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180522211438/http://content.time.com/time/subscriber/article/0,33009,931998,00.html|deadurl=no|quote=Died. Charles A. Whelan, 78, co-founder (with his brother) in 1901 of United Cigar Stores Co. of America which he sold in 1929 along with the Whelan Drug chain (founded by two of his sons)|access-date=January 1, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Two Morrows|work=Time|date=September 2, 1929|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,737772,00.html|archivedate=May 22, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180522211842/http://content.time.com/time/subscriber/article/0,33009,737772,00.html|deadurl=no|access-date=March 14, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The company also was involved in [[real estate]]. As the [[Great Depression]] deepened, the real-estate [[subsidiary]] accumulated huge losses, so in September 1932 the [[holding company]] declared [[bankruptcy]]. Before its bankruptcy, it had 975 cigar stores and 219 [[drug store]]s, but most of its [[assets]] were in real estate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Business: Cigar Stores|work=Time|date=1932-09-05|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,744307,00.html|archivedate=May 22, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180522211946/http://content.time.com/time/subscriber/article/0,33009,744307,00.html|deadurl=no|access-date=March 14, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The chain recovered and had 1300 outlets in 1951.<ref>{{cite news |title=Corporations: Battle for United Cigar |work=Time |date=October 15, 1951 |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,815565,00.html |archivedate=May 22, 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180522212142/http://content.time.com/time/subscriber/article/0,33009,815565,00.html |deadurl=no |access-date=March 14, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>
==Corporate progression== United Cigar Stores became part of United Cigar-Whelan Stores Corp.,{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}} then United Whelan Corp.<ref name=ca>{{cite web|last=Nadel |first=Nick |url=http://www.comicsalliance.com/2009/08/31/the-strange-business-history-of-marvel-comics/ |title=The Strange Business History of Marvel Comics |date=August 31, 2009 |publisher=Comics Alliance |accessdate=4 May 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319053209/http://www.comicsalliance.com/2009/08/31/the-strange-business-history-of-marvel-comics/ |archivedate=19 March 2012 |df= }}</ref> In 1962, it and three other companies merged to form [[Cadence Industries|Perfect Film & Chemical Corp.]], a film-processing and [[mail-order]] seller of [[drug]]s and [[vitamin]]s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Magazines" New Man for Curtis|work=Time|date=May 3, 1968|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,841264,00.html|archivedate=May 22, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180522212417/http://content.time.com/time/subscriber/article/0,33009,841264,00.html|deadurl=no|access-date=August 6, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=ca /> In 1968, it bought out publisher [[Martin Goodman (publisher)|Martin Goodman]], founder and owner of [[Magazine Management|Magazine Management Company]], the parent of [[Marvel Comics]] and other ventures.<ref name=ca /> The Company renamed itself Cadence Industries Corporation in 1970,<ref>{{cite web|title=Cadence Industries Corporation Entity Information (DOS ID #: 33485)|url=https://appext20.dos.ny.gov/corp_public/CORPSEARCH.ENTITY_INFORMATION?p_token=A0DCFB6A9400055E1BC213E81B30EEB5698813D0A239F3033D33CBF7F9C78B592BFB67519B711EB5D209771F5E3AF1D4&p_nameid=9EB20943C2889B3E&p_corpid=4171B7A26CA29237&p_captcha=11333&p_captcha_check=27E886988EE635BA&p_entity_name=%43%61%64%65%6E%63%65&p_name_type=%25&p_search_type=%42%45%47%49%4E%53&p_srch_results_page=2|publisher=[[New York State Department of State]], Division of Corporations|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref> and was liquidated in 1986, selling its [[Marvel Entertainment Group]] to [[New World Pictures]].<ref name=nyt1>{{cite news|last=Hicks|first=Jonathan|title=The Media Business; Marvel Comic Book Unit Being Sold for $82. 5 Million|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/11/08/business/the-media-business-marvel-comic-book-unit-being-sold-for-82.5-million.html|accessdate=May 5, 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 8, 1988}}</ref>
